Normalisation de lâassay RNA avec Seurat

NormalizeData()

NormalizeData() avec la mÃ©thode âLogNormalizeâ : soit x le nombre dâUMI dâun gÃ¨ne dÃ©tectÃ© dans une cellule. Pour normaliser cette donnÃ©e, on divise x par la somme de tous les UMIs dÃ©tectÃ©s pour tous les gÃ¨nes de cette cellule. Il est ensuite multipliÃ© par le scaling factor qui est par dÃ©faut Ã  10 000. On ajoute 1 au rÃ©sultat et on calcule ensuite son logarithme naturel (ln). (source de lâexplication du calcul : https://github.com/satijalab/seurat/issues/3630).
âLogNormalize scales the data by library size so it eliminates the confounding effect of different read depth across the cells.â

list_seurat_obj = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) { 
  NormalizeData(object = x, 
                assay = "RNA",
                normalization.method = "LogNormalize",
                scale.factor = 10000,
                verbose = TRUE) 
})

FindVariableFeatures()

FindVariableFeatures() sÃ©lectionne un sous-Ã©chantillon de gÃ¨nes Ã  garder pour la suite de lâanalyse. On choisit ici 2000 gÃ¨nes (nombre par dÃ©faut) qui correspondent aux gÃ¨nes prÃ©sentant le plus de variation entre les cellules, cad quâils sont fortement exprimÃ©s dans certaines cellules et faiblement pour dâautres. Pour extraire cette liste de gÃ¨nes, on utilise la mÃ©thode âvstâ : First, fits a line to the relationship of log(variance) and log(mean) using local polynomial regression. Then standardizes the feature values using the observed mean and expected variance (given by the fitted line). Feature variance is then calculated on the standardized values after clipping to a maximum (see clip.max parameter). Les prochaines analyses comme les UMAP ou PCA seront tracÃ©es sur la base de ces 2000 gÃ¨nes.

list_seurat_obj = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) { 
  FindVariableFeatures(object = x, 
                       assay = "RNA",
                       selection.method = 'vst',
                       nfeatures = "2000",   
                       verbose = TRUE) 
})

ScaleData()

linear transformation Shifts the expression of each gene, so that the mean expression across cells is 0 Scales the expression of each gene, so that the variance across cells is 1 This step gives equal weight in downstream analyses, so that highly-expressed genes do not dominate Pour le fait de faire un scaling diffÃ©rent en fonction du orig.ident, pourquoi pas. Ca peut potentiellement tirer un peu sur les gÃ¨nes qui ont des grosses disparitÃ©s entre conditions pour la PCA, mais câest pas forcÃ©ment un mal car câest ce qui tâintÃ©resse. Setting center to TRUE will center the expression for each feature by subtracting the average expression for that feature. Setting scale to TRUE will scale the expression level for each feature by dividing the centered feature expression levels by their standard deviations if center is TRUE and by their root mean square otherwise. Since highly expressed genes exhibit the highest amount of variation and we donât want our âhighly variable genesâ only to reflect high expression, we need to scale the data to scale variation with expression level. The Seurat ScaleData() function will scale the data by: adjusting the expression of each gene to give a mean expression across cells to be 0 scaling expression of each gene to give a variance across cells to be 1 https://hbctraining.github.io/scRNA-seq_online/lessons/06_SC_SCT_normalization.html premier scale sans rÃ©gression, il est possible de refaire un autre scale aprÃ¨s en rajoutant une rÃ©gression = > therefore overwriting the output of ScaleData()

list_seurat_obj = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) { 
  ScaleData(object = x, 
            assay = "RNA",
            split.by = "orig.ident",
            verbose = TRUE) 
})

Etude de lâinfluence du cycle cellulaire sur les variations observÃ©es

Pour Ã©tudier le cycle cellulaire, les donnÃ©es doivent avoir Ã©tÃ© prÃ©alablement normalisÃ©es et mises Ã  lâÃ©chelle. On utilise ensuite une liste de gÃ¨nes (contenue dans la fonction Seurat cc.genes) associÃ©s aux phases du cycle cellulaire S et G2M, pour associer un score Ã  chaque cellule les plaÃ§ant dans une phase ou lâautre. Les marqueurs sont anticorrÃ©lÃ©s dans les cellules et celles qui nâen expriment aucun ne sont pas en phase de division ou alors sont en phase G1.
Lâidentification de la phase du cycle cellulaire pour les cellules permettra de â mitigate the effects of cell cycle heterogeneity in scRNA-seq data by calculating cell cycle phase scores based on canonical markers, and regressing these out of the data during pre-processing.â.

list_seurat_obj = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) { 
  CellCycleScoring(object = x, 
                   assay = "RNA",
                   s.features = cc.genes$s.genes,
                   g2m.features = cc.genes$g2m.genes,
                   set.ident = TRUE,
                   verbose = TRUE) 
})

         assay = "RNA",

Visualisation du score de cycle cellulaire

# initialize list 
plot_cc_list = list()

for (i in 1:number_conditions) {
  
  name_obj = names(list_seurat_obj)[i]
  
  plot.s = VlnPlot(object = list_seurat_obj[[i]], features = "S.Score", 
                   group.by = "orig.ident", pt.size = 0.1, 
                   assay = "RNA", y.max = 1.5,
                   same.y.lims = TRUE) + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = color_code, limits = force) +
    ggtitle(paste0(name_obj, " - S.Score")) +
    NoLegend() +
    theme(axis.title.x = element_blank())
  
  plot.g2 = VlnPlot(object = list_seurat_obj[[i]], features = "G2M.Score", 
                    group.by = "orig.ident", pt.size = 0.1,
                    assay = "RNA", y.max = 1.5,
                    same.y.lims = TRUE) + 
    scale_fill_manual(values = color_code, limits = force) +
    ggtitle(paste0(name_obj, " - G2M.Score")) +
    NoLegend() +
    theme(axis.title.x = element_blank())
  
    cc_cond_pca = DimPlot(object = list_seurat_obj[[i]], 
                        reduction = "pca.cellcycle",
                        group.by = "Phase",
                        split.by = "orig.ident") + ggtitle(name_obj)
    
  plot_cc_list[[i]] = list(plot.s, plot.g2, cc_cond_pca)
  
}


grid.arrange(grobs = unlist(plot_cc_list, recursive = FALSE),
             ncol = 6,
             top = textGrob("Cell cycle scoring repartition"))

# Restriction des tableaux aux gÃ¨nes du cycle cellulaire
print("Filter genes to keep only cell cycle genes")
## [1] "Filter genes to keep only cell cycle genes"
list_mat = lapply(list_mat, function(x) { 
  x %>% dplyr::filter(row.names(x) %in% c(cc.genes$s.genes, cc.genes$g2m.genes)) 
})
  
# Extraction du nombre de cellules dÃ©tectant chaque gÃ¨ne et 
# des statistiques sur les UMI (total, moyenne, mÃ©diane, variance)
print("Calculate tab statistics")
## [1] "Calculate tab statistics"
list_mat = lapply(list_mat, function(x) {
    print("Calculate temp_nbcells tab")
    temp_nbcells = x
    ncol_temp_nbcells = ncol(temp_nbcells)
    temp_nbcells[] = lapply(temp_nbcells, as.logical)
    temp_nbcells = temp_nbcells %>% 
      dplyr::mutate(nbcells = rowSums(.)) %>%
      dplyr::mutate(percentcells = round((nbcells/ncol_temp_nbcells) *100)) %>%
      tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "gene") %>%
      dplyr::select(gene, nbcells, percentcells)
    print("Calculate temp_umi tab")
    temp_umi = x 
    temp_umi = temp_umi %>%
      dplyr::mutate(totalUMI = rowSums(.),
                    medianUMI = rowMedians(as.matrix(temp_umi[,-totalUMI])),
                    meanUMI = round(rowMeans(as.matrix(temp_umi[,c(-totalUMI, -medianUMI)])), 2),
                    varUMI = round(rowVars(as.matrix(temp_umi[,c(-totalUMI, -medianUMI, -meanUMI)])), 2)) %>%
      tibble::rownames_to_column(var = "gene") %>%
      dplyr::mutate(phase = ifelse(gene %in% cc.genes$s.genes, "S", "G2M")) %>% 
      dplyr::select(gene, phase, totalUMI, meanUMI, medianUMI, varUMI)
    x = full_join(temp_nbcells, temp_umi, by = "gene")
    return(x)
  })

PossibilitÃ© de rÃ©gresser les donnÃ©es ou non => la rÃ©gression se fait au niveau de la normalisation SCT.

Normalisation de lâassay RNA avec SCTransform

La fonction SCTransform regroupe en une seule ligne des filtres sur les donnÃ©es, une normalisation, lâextraction des 2000 gÃ¨nes les plus variables et le scaling. On utilise la mÃ©thode âglmGamPoiâ dans la fonction SCTransform pour amÃ©liorer la vitesse de calcul. Les rÃ©sultats de la normalisation sont ensuite stockÃ©s dans lâassay âSCTâ.
Filtres appliquÃ©s: Attention, les paramÃ¨tres de filtre par dÃ©faut sont âcachÃ©sâ dans la fonction SCTransform. - Filter out cells which have less than this many genes expressed [200] => notre filtre est plus restrictif (1000 gÃ¨nes) donc pas dâimpact - Filter out cells which have higher unique gene count [2500] => pas trouvÃ© comment lâenlever, câest beaucoup plus restrictif que nos propres filtres - Filter out cells which have higher mitochondrial transcript percentage [5] avec min_cells = 1, on enlÃ¨ve le filtre min_cells that only use genes that have been detected in at least this many cells; default is 5 On regarde donc les paramÃ¨tres disponibles dans la fonction vst de base et on les rajoute dans SCTransform pour avoir la main sur les filtres appliquÃ©s. Comme on applique dÃ©jÃ  des filtres sur nos donnÃ©es en prÃ© processing, on va faire en sorte dâannuler les filtres par dÃ©faut. https://rdrr.io/cran/sctransform/man/vst.html Normalisation : Expression values are normalized using the SCTransform normalisation method, which uses Pearson residuals from âregularized negative binomial regression,â where cellular sequencing depth is utilized as a covariate in a generalized linear model (GLM). The parameters for the model are estimated by pooling information acreoss genes that are expressing at similar levels. This should remove the technical characteristics but preserve the biological heterogeneity, and avoid overfitting the model to the data. center residuals to have mean zero

âCompared to basic Seurat normalisation + scaling + variable gene finding, the SCTransform workflow performs more effective normalization, strongly removing technical effects from the data. This allows more PCs to be selected in the PCA step, as the higher PCs are more likely to represent subtle, but biologically relevant, sources of heterogeneity instead of variation in sequencing depth.â

# On ne peut pas faire les deux normalisations dans le mÃªme objets car la deuxiÃ¨me efface la premiÃ¨re

# SC normalization with cell cycle regression
list_seurat_obj_cc = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) { 
  SCTransform(object = x, 
              assay = "RNA", 
              # new.assay.name = "SCT_with_ccreg", 
              new.assay.name = "SCT",
              method = "glmGamPoi", 
              do.center = TRUE, 
              do.scale = FALSE,
              variable.features.n = 3000,
              vars.to.regress = c("S.Score", "G2M.Score"),
              min_cells = 1,
              ncells = NULL,
              verbose = FALSE) 
})

# SC normalization without cell cycle regression
list_seurat_obj = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) { 
  SCTransform(object = x, 
              assay = "RNA", 
              # new.assay.name = "SCT_without_ccreg", 
              new.assay.name = "SCT",
              method = "glmGamPoi", 
              do.center = TRUE, 
              do.scale = FALSE,
              variable.features.n = 3000,
              vars.to.regress = NULL,
              min_cells = 1,
              ncells = NULL,
              verbose = FALSE)
  
})

Normalisation de lâassay ADT avec LogNormalisation

Normalization method CLR applies a centered log ratio transformation, with parameter margin = 2 the normalisation is performing across cells.

list_seurat_obj = lapply(list_seurat_obj, function(x) {
  NormalizeData(object = x, 
                normalization.method = "CLR",
                margin = 2,
                assay = "ADT")
})
